Arbitrary inlet (half-disk patch)
================================

Demonstrates the syntheticTurbulenceInlet on a non-canonical patch
using geometryMode "arbitrary". In this mode the BC does not assume
any specific geometric structure (annulus/disk/rectangle/channel) and
does not interpolate from the bundled DNS profiles; it uses the last
entry of the R and L tables uniformly across the patch, producing
isotropic-ish synthetic turbulence on whatever shape the patch is.

Geometry            Half-disk inlet, radius R = 0.025 m in the y-z
                    plane (diameter along y at z = 0, semicircle
                    above), extruded L = 0.001 m along x.
Inlet target        Umean = 10 m/s.
Friction velocity   Auto-computed from the bulk Reynolds number.
Solver              foamRun, incompressibleFluid.

Run with:           ./Allrun
Clean with:         ./Allclean

Notes
-----
- "arbitraryModeRadius" and "arbitraryModeCenter" can be set
  explicitly in 0/U; if absent (as here), the BC uses the largest
  face-vertex distance from the patch centroid as the radius and the
  centroid itself as the center.
- In arbitrary mode the defaults for "scale" (0.2) and "nCellPerEddy"
  (5) differ from the other geometryModes (where both default to 1),
  since there is no DNS-calibrated profile to anchor the eddy
  intensity and size.
- The half-disk inlet is produced in blockMesh from a single hex
  block with three arc edges per end (left, top, right of the
  semicircle); the fourth edge (the diameter, z = 0) is straight.
- system/patchSurface writes the inlet U field to VTK every 1 ms of
  simulation time so the eddies can be inspected in ParaView while
  the case is still running.
